Rebuilding from those sources with a modified LGPL library reproduces the
binary. Because latexml-oxide's own source is CC0, nothing in our terms
restricts you from doing so.

Requests for the corresponding sources: https://github.com/dginev/latexml-oxide/issues

3.6 unidecode — transliteration data from Text::Unidecode
---------------------------------------------------------

Not a C library, but listed here for the same reason: the manifest names a
different holder than the material shipped. The `unidecode` crate embeds a ~1.9 MB
Unicode→ASCII mapping table machine-generated from Sean M. Burke's Perl
`Text::Unidecode` (its README says so; `src/data.rs` is headed "File autogenerated
with /scripts/generate_map.pl").

      The Rust crate:  Copyright (c) 2015 Amit Chowdhury.
          BSD 3-Clause, as its manifest declares — attributed in section 5.

      The mapping data:  Copyright (c) 2001, 2014, 2015, 2016 Sean M. Burke.
          "Under the same terms as Perl itself" — Artistic-1.0-Perl OR
          GPL-1.0-or-later.  https://metacpan.org/pod/Text::Unidecode

The crate's BSD-3-Clause covers its Rust code and does not, on its face, account
for the upstream data's terms. We treat the table as uncopyrightable data — a
factual mapping, much of it derived from the Unicode Consortium's own — so no
copyleft attaches and no Artistic/GPL text ships in section 6. That is a
judgement, not a certainty; hence writing it down. Burke's attribution is owed
either way, and given.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Graphics tools — invoked as subprocesses, never linked
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Graphics conversion optionally shells out to Ghostscript (`gs`, AGPL-3.0),
MuPDF (`mutool`, AGPL-3.0), Poppler (`pdftocairo`, GPL-2.0), and ImageMagick
(`convert`). In the binary downloads these come from the user's own system and
are invoked only as separate processes (never linked), so their copyleft terms
do not extend to this binary.

Exception: our container images `apt-get install` these tools (and TeX Live)
INTO the image, so there they are redistributed, not borrowed. They stay
separate programs merely aggregated alongside latexml-oxide — which does not
place latexml-oxide under their terms — and each carries its own Ubuntu
copyright file under /usr/share/doc.
